
<leme no="343">

<set tag="expression" lang="en">

<page no="3" sig="A2r">
<section type="Title page">
<f type="rl">THE
ENGLISH
DICTIONARIE:
OR,
AN INTERPRETER<f type="r">
<f type="r">of hard English Words.
Enabling as well Ladies and Gentle&shy;
women, young Schollers, Clarkes, Merchants,
as also Strangers of any Nation to the vnder&shy;
standing of the more difficult Authors already
printed in our Language, and the more
<f type="i">speedy attaining of an elegant perfection of
<f type="r">the English tongue, both in reading,
speaking and writing.
Being a Collection of some thousands of words,
neuer published by any heretofore.
<p>

By <f type="i">H. C.<f type="r"> Gent.<f type="r">
<f type="rl">LONDON.<f type="r">
<f type="r">Printed for <f type="i">Nathaniel Butter<f type="r">, and are 
to be sold at his shop, at S<f type="r"><f type="+">t<f type="i">. Austins
gate, at the signe of the <f type="i">Pide-Bull<f type="r">.
1623.<f type="r">
</section>
</page>

<page no="4" sig="A2v">
</page>

<page no="5" sig="A3r">
<section type="Dedication epistle">
<f type="rl">TO THE RIGHT HO&shy;<f type="r">
nourable, Sir <f type="i">Richard Boyle<f type="r">, Knight, 
Lord <f type="i">Boyle<f type="r">, Baron of <f type="i">Youghall<f type="r">, Viscount <f type="i">Dun&shy;
garuan<f type="r">, Earle of <f type="i">Cork<f type="r">, and one of his Maie&shy;
sties most Honourable Priuie Councell 
of the Kingdome of <f type="i">Ireland<f type="r">, &amp;c.<f type="r">
<f type="bk">P<f type="i">Art of euery desertfull birth, 
(Right Honourable) in any man 
his Country may challenge, his 
Soueraigne a part, his Parents a
part, &amp; his friends another. As I 
cannot be vseful in euery respect to each of those, 
so I will striue to expresse at least a will, if not a 
perfection in abilitie to all. Where a generall 
voice warrants an approbation, there euery ser&shy;
uice is a duty. The truth of it both concernes and 
inuites me, out of the fame and applause of your 
Noblenesse, to make a particular dedication of 
some serious houres to your suruey, whom the 
world speakes both noble and learned, wherein 
as I haue done my best to accommodate discourse 
</page>

<page no="6" sig="A3v">
<f type="i">with the choisest language, so I desire that my 
ambition of being knowne vnto your Lordship 
may not be imputed either vnto an errour of im&shy;
pudence, or an impudence in erring. Please you 
to know thus much of me, that I am partly im&shy;
boldned hereunto, by the assurance of your loue 
and fauours to that noble Gentleman, <f type="r">Sir Wil&shy;
liam Hull<f type="i">, to whom as I am tied in double 
bonds of bloud and friendship, so, I am so much 
obliged vnto him, that I cannot deuise a better 
rent than to doe you seruice : But chiefely the re&shy;
port of your owne honourable merit and iust 
commendations, encourage mee to this duty, 
though otherwise vnknowne, not questioning 
but you will be pleased to take notice of one who 
loues and honours vertue in all Personages for 
vertues sake. Vouchsafe (Right Honourable)
this poore testimonie of my obseruancie, intended 
only to serue you, not to instruct you, and you shall 
not onely largely requite my endeuours, but 
may also expect a more steady and particular du&shy;
ty from<f type="r">
<f type="r">Your Honours most ready seruant,
<f type="i">Henry Cockeram.<f type="r">
</section>
</page>

<page no="7" sig="A4r">
<section type="Preface">
<heading><f type="r">A Premonition from the 
Author to the Reader.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">I <f type="r">Am not ignorant of the 
praise-worthy labours which 
some Schollers of deserued 
memorie haue heretofore be&shy;
stowed on the like subiect 
that I haue here aduentured on :
howsoeuer it might therefore 
seeme a needlesse taske of mine, to intrude vp&shy;
on a plot of study, the foundation of whose buil&shy;
ding hath beene formerly leuel'd and laid, yet the 
Iustice of defence herein is so cleere, that my en&shy;
deuours may bee truly termed rather a necessity 
of doing, than an arrogancie in doing. For 
without appropriating to my owne comfort any 
interest of glory, the <f type="i">vnderstanding<f type="r"> Readers will 
not, the <f type="i">ignorant<f type="r"> cannot, and the <f type="i">malicious<f type="r">
dare not, but acknowledge that what any before
me in this kinde haue begun, I haue not onely<f type="r">
</page>

<page no="8" sig="A4v">
<f type="r">fully finished, but throughly perfected. To write 
an Apologie of iustification would argue rather 
a distrust of my Worke than a confidence of me&shy;
rit :  Be pleased therefore (honest and (therin)
learned Reader) to suruey a short Premonition 
for the order of the ensuing Vocabularie. First 
the method is plaine and easie, being alphabeti&shy;
call, by which the capacity of the meanest may 
soone be inlightened. The first Booke hath the 
choisest words themselues now in vse, where&shy;
with our language is inriched and become so 
copious, to which words the common sense is 
annexed. The second Booke containes the 
vulgar words, which whensoeuer any desirous 
of a more curious explanation by a more refi&shy;
ned and elegant speech shall looke into, he shall 
there receiue the exact and ample word to ex&shy;
presse the same : Wherein by the way let me pray 
thee to obserue that I haue also inserted (as occa&shy;
sion serued) euen the <f type="i">mocke-words <f type="r">which are ridi&shy;
culously vsed in our language, that those who 
desire a generality of knowledge may not bee 
ignorant of the sense, euen of the <f type="i">fustian 
termes<f type="r">, vsed by too many who study rather 
to bee heard speake, than to vnderstand them&shy;
selues. The last Booke is a recitall of seuerall per&shy;
sons, Gods and Goddesses, Giants and Deuils, 
Monsters and Serpents, Birds and Beasts, Riuers, 
Fishes, Herbs, Stones, Trees, and the like, to 
the intent that the diligent learner may not pre&shy;<f type="r">
</page>

<page no="9" sig="A5r">
<f type="r">tend the defect of any helpe which may informe 
his discourse or practice. I might insist vpon the 
generall vse of this worke, especially for La&shy;
dies and Gentlewomen, Clarkes, Merchants, 
young Schollers, Strangers, Trauellers, and all 
such as desire to know the plenty of the English;
but I am confident, that experience will be the 
truest Herauld to publish to the world on my be&shy;
halfe, how as my debt to my countrie is to bee 
challenged, so my Country shall not altogether 
boast of any immunity from being indebted to 
my Studies. Thus what I haue done is (Reader)
for thy benefit, accept it and make vse of it, so 
shall I finde reward in my labours, and rest thy 
friend,<f type="r">
<f type="i">H. C.
</section>
</page>

<page no="10" sig="A5v">
</page>

<page no="11" sig="A6r">
<section type="Poem of compliment">
<heading><f type="r">To his very good friend, Master <f type="r">
<f type="i">Henry Cockeram<f type="r">, on his Vo&shy;
cabulary.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="i">He whose selfe loue, or too ambitious spirit,
Enuies or carpes at this thy Muses action,
Nere let him liue, or of a Muse once merit,
Regard or fame, but die in his detraction,
Irreuocably plagu'd with Zoilan spight,
Ere he once taste of Hellicons delight.

Could I, oh could I quintessence my skill,
Or with Elixir truly alcumize,
Knowledge with learning should instruct my quill.
Effectually to praise thy Muses guise,
Re-felling all the criticall disasters,
Among some captious, yet wise seeming masters,
Made by her curious eye, their owne distasters.<f type="r">
<f type="r">Nicholas Smith<f type="i">, <term lang="la">Eques Auratus 
Encomiastes Posthumus.<f type="r"></term>
</page>

<page no="12" sig="A6v">
<heading><f type="r">To my industrious freind, the Au&shy;
thor of this English Dictionarie,
Mr. <f type="r"><f type="rl">HENRY COCKRAM<f type="r">
of <f type="r"><f type="rl">EXETER.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">B<f type="i">Orne in the West? liue there? so far fr<expan type="o+_">om</expan> Court?
Fr<expan type="o+_">om</expan> <f type="r">Oxford, Cambridge, London? <f type="i">yet report
(Now in these daies of Eloquence) such change
Of words? vnknown? vntaught? tis new &amp; strange.
Let Gallants therefore skip no more from hence 
To <f type="r">Italie, France, Spaine, <f type="i">and with expence 
Waste time and faire estates, to learne new fashions 
Of complementall phrases, smooth temptations
To glorious beggary : Here let them hand<f type="r">
<f type="r">This Book; <f type="i"> here studie, reade, and vnderstand :
Then shall they finde varietie at <f type="r">Home,<f type="i">
As curious as at <f type="r">Paris,<f type="i"> or at <f type="r">Rome.<f type="i">
For my part I confesse, hadst not thou writ, 
I had not beene acquainted with more wit
Than our old English taught; but now I can 
Be proud to know I haue a Countryman
Hath strugled for a fame, and what is more, 
Gain'd it by paths of Art, vntrod before.
</page>

<page no="13" sig="A7r">
The benefit is generall; the crowne
Of praise particular, and thats <f type="r">thine owne.<f type="i">
What should I say? Thine owne deserts inspire thee, 
Twere base to enuie, I must then admire thee.<f type="r">
<f type="r">A friend and louer of thy paines,<f type="r">
<f type="rl">IOHN FORD.<f type="r">
</page>

<page no="14" sig="A7v">
<heading><f type="i">To the Reader on this Verball of his 
esteemed friend, Master <f type="i">Henry Cocke&shy;
ram <f type="r">of <f type="i">Exeter.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">A<f type="i">Rt hidden moulds, the Author freely sends, 
His sweat of brow to publike priuat friends, 
His courtesie to labour, yours to raise,
As it deserues the countenance of praise.
Hard words far fetch'd, made smooth, before being <hungword>rough,</hungword>
Claime fauour for requitall, that's enough.
If you betray them with a trecherous kisse,
He'l laugh in's sleeue, and at your follies hisse.<f type="r">
<f type="r">Thomas Spicer.<f type="r">

<heading><f type="r">To the Reader on this Vocabulary 
of his good friend, Master <f type="i">Henry Cocke&shy;
ram <f type="r">of <f type="i">Exeter.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">I<f type="i">F things farre fetch'd are dearest most esteem'd, 
which by times sweatful houres haue been redeem'd, 
Of what count's this,of which sort like was neuer, 
Praise it of force you must, and loue him euer.
The <f type="r">Adage<f type="i"> is far sought, deare bought, please ladies, 
You must yeeld to this Maxime, or proue babies.
Then giue worths due, that worthinesses guise,
If not, my Motto is, you are vnwise.<f type="r">
<f type="r">Bartho. Hore.<f type="r">
</page>

<page no="15" sig="A8r">
<heading><f type="r">To my very good friend, Master <f type="i">Co&shy;
keram, <f type="r">Author of this worke.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">T<f type="i">O speake good words of thee were but in part 
To pay backe what we owe, for thy rare Art 
Hath taught vs all good language : a rude pile 
Of barbarous sillables into a stile
Gentle and smooth thou hast reduc't : pure gold 
Thou hast extracted out of worthlesse mould.
And that no one may thinke thy merit weake, 
Of a rough speech th'ast taught vs all to speake
A perfect language ; in which <f type="r">Cockerams<f type="i"> praise
Shall liue belou'd, whilst time leaues making daies. <f type="r">
<f type="r">Iohn Day.<f type="r">

<heading><f type="r">To his industrious friend, Master <f type="r">
<f type="i">Henry Cockeram.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">T<f type="i">O ouer-praise thy Booke, in a smooth line,
(If any errour's in't) would make it mine :
Onely, while Words, for paiment passe at Court;
And whilst loud talke and wrangling make resort 
I'th Terme to Westminster, I doe not dread
Thy leaues shall scape the Scombri, and be read.
And I will adde this as thy friend, no Poet,
Thou hast toild to purpose, and the euent will shew it.<f type="r">
<f type="r">Iohn Webster.<f type="r">
</page>

<page no="16" sig="A8v">
<heading><f type="r">To his worthily respected friend, 
Master <f type="i">Henry Cockeram.<f type="r"></heading>

<f type="bk">W<f type="i">Ho hath discouer'd yet a neerer way,
By which, what we conceiue, we can conuey
To others, then by words, that full expresse
What <f type="r">Mimicke<f type="i"> action doth but onely guesse:
But where a language hath variety,
And euery word a reall property,
How much it adds to elocution,
As doe but reade this Booke, then thinke vpon 
The Authors paines and praise, giue him respect 
For this addition to our Dialect.<f type="r">

<f type="r">Iohn Crugge.<f type="r">
</section>
</page>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="climacterical(a)"><f type="i">Clymactericall.</form> <xpln><f type="r">Is euerie
seuenth yeere, which is held 
very dangerous, and by this 
account the 14, 21, 28, 35, 
&amp;c. are held clymactericall 
yeeres: some hold the 
ninth yeere to be the cly&shy;
mactericall yere, & as dan&shy;
gerous as the other: and by 
this account 18, 27, 36, &amp;c.
are so called: But the most 
dangerous and notedst cli&shy;
mactericall yeere is at the 
age of 63. for that both ac&shy;
counts doe meet in this 
number, namely, 9. times 
seuen, and 7. times 9. either 
of which numbers make 
63. this (I say) is held the 
most dangerous yeere of 
all.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="collateral(a)"><f type="i">Collaterall.</form> <xpln><f type="r">Sidewaies: eue&shy;
ry degree of kindred is 
either lineall or collate&shy;
rall: the lineall is that 
which commeth from the 
grandfather to the father, 
and from the father to the 
sonne, and so still right
downewards: collaterall is
that which commeth side&shy;
waies, as first between bro&shy;
thers and sisters, then be&shy;
tweene their children, &amp;c.
Also vncles, aunts, and all 
cousens are contained vn&shy;
der this terme of collate&shy;
rall kindred.</xpln>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="fenchmonth(n)"><f type="i">Fenchmonth.</form> <xpln><f type="r">A moneth
wherein Does doe Fawne,
it begins about the ninth
of Iune, and continueth
vntill the ninth of Iuly, in
which time it is not lawfull
to hunt in any Forrest. In
the Fenchmonth, it is not
lawfull for any Cart or Pa&shy;
niers to passe through any
Forrest without paying
fees: which fee, for a paire
of Wheeles is foure pence,
and for Paniers two pence,
which fee being once paid
they may for that season
freely passe.</xpln>
</wordentry>

taining nine degrees (as

resemblance of the Trini&shy;
tie, there being in nine
thrice three, and in euery
three thrice one; so that
there are three superiours,
three inferiours, and three
middle degrees: the supe&shy;
riour are Seraphins, Che&shy;
rubins, and Thrones; the
middle are Dominations, 
Principalities, Powers;
the Inferiour, Vertues,

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="hieroglyphics(n)"><f type="i">Hieroglyphicks.</form> <xpln><f type="r">A mysti&shy;
call kinde of writing, vsed
in ancient time by Pagans,
Priests, and the like: This
kinde of writing was by
making the forme of beasts
and the like, and could
hardly bee vnderstood (e&shy;
specially of the vulgar 
sort) without great know&shy;
ledge of the nature of 
things: As for example, e&shy;
ternitie they expressed by a 
round circle which hath no 
end: a King, by a Scepter, 
with an eye in the top 
thereof: a matter of haste, 
by a Dolphin, the swiftest 
of all Fishes: and a matter 
of aduice or deliberation, 
by an Anchor which staies 
a ship in the waues, with a 
thousand such deuices not 
subiect to common capaci&shy;
ties to finde out.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Nazarite(pn)"><f type="i">Nazarite.</form> <xpln><f type="r">The <f type="i">Iewes <f type="r">so
called those that vowed
themselues sometime to
God, and while their vow
lasted, they abstained from
all kinde of Wine, nor
could they drinke any
thing which might make
them drunke, they neuer
cut their haire, but did suf&shy;
fer it still to grow: their
vow expired, they presen&shy;
ted themselues to the 
Priests, who offered a Sa&shy;
crifice for them, and then 
was their haire cut, and 
burnt therewith, and then 
they might drinke any 
thing, as before.</xpln>

ueth; there are two such

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="pollard(n)"><f type="i">Pollard,</form> <xpln><f type="r">Is a Stagge, or
any other male Deere, ha&shy;
uing cast his head, which
time is in March and April,
then he is said to musen;
Butten is the first part in
putting vp a Stagges head,
hauing cast his hornes;
Beame is that whereon the
starts of the head growes;
Brow antler is the first start
that growes next the head;
Beame antler is the next
start growing aboue the
Brow antler; Broach is the
next growing aboue the
Beame antler; Royall is
the next growing aboue
the Broach; Torch royall
is the next growing aboue
the Royall; Torch is the
next growing aboue the
Royal, which makes a com&shy;
pleat Stags head, being full
growne: Sumn'd or full, is
when a Stags head is fully
hardned; Burnishing, is
when a Stag rubs and beats
off his veluet head: a Stag
hunted by a King or Prince
is called a Hart.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="predicament(n)"><f type="i">Predicament.</form> <xpln><f type="r">A diffe&shy;
rent order in the nature of
things or certaine gene&shy;
rall heads, to which they
may be referred: and there
are commonly reckoned
ten such predicaments; the
first called Substance, in&shy;
cludeth all substances what&shy;
soeuer, as the foure Ele&shy;
ments and all other crea&shy;
tures. The second named
Quantitie, containeth all
quantities, as ten, twen&shy;
tie, a furlong, a mile.  The
third called Qualitie, hath
vnder it all qualities, as wis&shy;
dome, art, sloth, forti&shy;
tude.  The fourth named
Relation, is properly of
such words as depend mu&shy;
tually one vpon another,
as a husband and wife,
father and childe, master
and seruant.  The other 
six are; Fifth, Action or 
doing.  Sixth, Passion or 
suffering.  Seuenth, Where.
Eighth, When.  Ninth, Si&shy;
tuation or placing.  Tenth,
The habit or outward co&shy;
uering of a thing.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="syllogism(n)"><f type="i">Syllogisme.</form> <xpln><f type="r">An argument
consisting of three parts,
whereby something is ne&shy;
cessarily proued, as thus;
Euery vertue is honoura&shy;
ble: Patience is a vertue;
Therefore Patience is ho&shy;
nourable.  The first part of
a Syllogisme is called the
Proposition or Maior; the
second, the Assumption or
Minor; and the third, the

<section type="The Third Part">
<heading>
<f type="i">THE THIRD PART TREA&shy;
TING OF GODS AND GOD&shy;
desses, Men and Women, Boyes and Maides, Gi&shy;
<f type="i">ants and Diuels, Birds and Beasts, Monsters
and Serpents, Wells and Riuers, Hearbs,
Stones, Trees, Dogges, Fishes,
and the like.</heading>

<wordgroup1 type="t" object="Of beasts"><f type="i">Of Beasts.

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="armadillo(n)"><f type="i">ARmadilio<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a beast
in India like vn&shy;
to a young Pigge
couered ouer 
with smal shels like vn&shy;
to armour: it liues like
a Mole in the ground.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="babboon(n)"><f type="i">Baboone<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a beast like an
Ape, but farre bigger.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="beaver(n)"><f type="i">Beauer<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a very hot beast
of nature, liuing much in
the water: his stones are
much vsed in Phisick, and
of great esteeme, but not
so much esteemed as his
skinne.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="boar(n)"><f type="i">Bore of Pannonia<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> the cru&shy;
elst of all other Bores.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="buff(n)"><f type="i">Buffe<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a very fierce beast,
much like vnto a Bull, ha&shy;
uing a very long mane.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="chamelion(n)"><f type="i">Chamelions<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> the least of all
beasts, which breeds egges
or spawne, it changeth it
selfe into any colour that
it sits on, except white &amp;
red: therefore incon&shy;
stant men are sometimes
called Chamelions: it is
said it onely liues by the
ayre.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="crocodile(n)"><f type="i">Crocodile<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a beast hatched
of an egge, yet some of
them grow to a great big&shy;
nesse, as 10. 20. or 30. foot
in length: it hath cruell
teeth and scaly back, with
very sharpe clawes on his
feete: if it see a man afraid
of him, it will eagerly pur&shy;
sue him, but on the con&shy;
trary, if he be assaulted he
will shun him. Hauing eat<expan type="e+_">en</expan>
the body of a man, it will
weepe ouer the head, but
in fine eate the head also:
thence came the Prouerb,
he shed. Crocodile teares,
</page>

<page sig="g6v">
viz. fayned teares.</xpln>
</wordentry>
<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="ermine(n)"><f type="i">Ermynes<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a small beast,
lesse then a Squirrell, the
Fur whereof is most cost&shy;
ly: onely worne by Prin&shy;
ces.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="eveck(n)"><f type="i">Eueck<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a wilde kinde of
beast, much like a Goat.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="giraffe(n)"><f type="i">Giraffe<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a wilde beast li&shy;
uing in the Deserts, if it
see a man it flies foorth&shy;
with: but being taken, it is
easily tamed: his legges
and feete are like vnto a 
Deere, with a neck as long
as a warlike Pick, with
two hornes in his head, and
long haire on his neck.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="hippopotamus(n)"><f type="i">Hippopotomus<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a fierce
beast liuing in the riuer
Nilus.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="hiena(n)"><f type="i">Hiena<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a subtill beast like
a Woolfe, hauing a mane
and haire on his body, 
counterfaiting the voyce
of a man: in the night it
will call shepheards out of
their houses, &amp; kill them:
hee is sometime male and
sometime female.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="ignarus(n)"><f type="i">Ignarus<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a small beast
without a tayle, hauing
small legges, with three
long sharpe clawes, in&shy;
steed of feete, wherewith
hee runneth vp trees, and
his desire is to sit there on
the tops thereof: it was
neuer seene to feede on
any thing, and therefore
is supposed to liue by the
ayre: in the night it sing&shy;
eth sixe kind of notes one
after another: as, <f type="I">la-sol-fa&shy;
mi-re-vt<f type="r">: it is not aboue
eighteen inches in length,
and is neere as thicke as
long: his head resembles
an Ape, but he hath very
little eyes and mouth, and
hath long bristled haire:
it is the slowest of all
beasts, for fifty paces is a
whole dayes iourney for 
him.</xpln>
<lemenote>cf. OED ingram, slouk"</lemenote>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="libbard(n)"><f type="i">Libard<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a spotted wilde
beast, the male of a Pan&shy;
ther.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Molarchea(pn)" lexeme="Cleonia(pn)" lexeme="lion(n)"><f type="i">Lion of Cleonia<f type="r">, and <f type="i">Mo&shy;
larchea<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> are two the most

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="lizard(n)"><f type="i">Lizard<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a little beast

without poyson, breeding
in Italy and other Coun&shy;
tries, the doung of this
beast is good to take away
the spots in the eye, and
cleareth the sight, and the
</page>

<page sig="g7r">
head thereof being brused
and layed to, draweth out
thornes, or any thing stic&shy;
king in the flesh.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="lynx(n)"><f type="i">Lynx<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a spotted beast,
much like a Woolfe, it
hath a most perfect sight,
in so much as it is said that
it can see through a wall.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="panther(n)"><f type="i">Panther<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a cruell beast

faire spotted skin, where&shy;
with shee allureth other
beasts to looke on her, but
least her head should af&shy;
fright them, she hideth it,
and by this meanes shee
getteth her prey more ea&shy;
sily.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="rhinoceros(n)"><f type="i">Rinocere<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a beast as bigge
as an Elephant, but thicker
and higher, they are vtter
enemies and alwayes com&shy;
bat when they meete: he
hath a horne in his nose
bending vpward, which he
whetteth gainst the rocks
for his defence.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="salamander(n)"><f type="i">Salamander<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a small ve&shy;
nomous beast with foure
feete, and a short taile, it
liues in the fire, and at
length by his extreame
colde puts out the fire.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="chamois(n)"><f type="i">Shamoyse<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a wilde Goate,

</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="shrew(n)"><f type="i">Shrew<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a kinde of wilde
Mouse, which if it goe o&shy;
uer a beasts backe, will
make it lame in the chine,
and if it bite, the beast
swelleth to the heart and
dieth.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="sue(n)"><f type="i">Sue<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a most cruell fierce
beast, carrying her young
vpon her backe to shadow
them from the heat with
her huge taile.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="tiger(n)"><f type="i">Tyger<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a truculent beast,
and the swiftest of all o&shy;
ther beasts: wherefore
they are taken very young
in the dams absence, and
carried away by them on
horsebacke: who hearing
the crie of the olde Tyger
following after them, doe
of purpose let fall one of
the whelpes, that while
shee beareth that backe,
they in the meane time
may escape safe with the
other to the ship: but of
all, the <f type="i">Hircan<f type="r"> Tyger is the
most cruelst.
</xpln>
</wordentry>

<lemeformat>

  Lately a Mushrompe,

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="griffin(n)"><f type="i">Griffin<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a foure footed

daring to aduenture on a
man, he is a great enemie
to horses, as sayeth <f type="i">Virgill<f type="r">
in his eight Eglogge: <f type="i">The
Griffins fierce are ioyn'd with
horses now<f type="r">, speaking of a
strange marriage: from the
breast vpward this bird is
fashion'd Eagle-like, of
purple colour with fiery
eyes, and whitish wings,
his hinder part is made Li&shy;
on like, hee is exceeding
hard to bee taken vnlesse
very young, and nesteth in
high mountaines; he is so
fierce that often he killeth
Elephants and Dragons.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="harpy(n)"><f type="i">Harpies<f type="r"></form>, <xpln lexeme="Aello(pn)" lexeme="Ocypete(pn)" lexeme="Celeno(pn)" lexeme="Thyella(pn)"> monstrous de&shy;

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="phoenix(n)"><f type="i">Phenix<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> the rarest bird
in the world, liuing onely
in Arabia, here was ne&shy;
uer but one at a time in
the world, it is of the big&shy;
nes of an Eagle, of colour
purple, with a bright col&shy;
ler of golde about his
necke, a goodly taile, and
a tuft of feathers on his
head, he liueth aboue 600.
yeares, and being olde,
buildeth him an nest of
Cinamon, and the twigges
of Frankincense, which
he filleth with Spices, and
with the labouring of his
wings in the Sunne, set&shy;
teth it on fire, and is there
consumed in it, out of
whose ashes there groweth
a worme, and of the worme
another Phenix.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="stork(n)"><f type="i">Storke<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a famous bird for

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="tragoponadus(n)"><f type="i">Tragoponadus<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a bird in

shore, who with their

into the Sea, but seeing
himselfe bound and ouer&shy;
mastered is easily tamed,
then they kill him and
skinne him, take out his
fat, and cut his skin into
thonges, which are sold
for a great price, as being
very strong, and will ne&shy;
uer rot.</xpln>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Aglaia(pn)"  lexeme="Thalia(pn)" lexeme="Euphrosyne(pn)"><f type="i">AGlaia, Thalia, Euphro&shy;
syne<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> so were they cal&shy;
led, they were three sisters
supposed to be the daugh&shy;
ters of <f type="i">Iupiter<f type="r"> and <f type="i">Venus<f type="r">:
the morallity of this in&shy;
uention was to expresse
the cheerfull conuersation 
which ought to be amongst
friends, for they were
painted naked, to signifie
that friendship, ought to
be plaine without dissimu&shy;
lation, smiling and merry:
to shew that men should
doe good willingly: young
and maydenlike, to teach
that friendship should
consist in honest things:
and holding hands toge&shy;
ther in a round ring, to
shew that a benefit besto&shy;
wed, doth againe returne
to the giuer.</xpln>
</wordentry>
</wordgroup1>

many of his friends) made

a small iron Fly to creepe
out vnder his hand, and
flye about all the roome,
and returne and pitch on
his sleeue. Hee likewise
made an iron Eagle to flie
and meete an Almane Em&shy;
peror at his outmost gate,
and to returne into the
Pallace with him.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<f type="i">Phaleris<f type="r"> the tyrant, who

men scoffed, saying: there
hung a tankerd and no
man.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Darius(pn)"><f type="i">Darius<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> was an exceed&shy;

and beare it well.</xpln>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Mylo(pn)"><f type="i">Mylo<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> once euery day

thereby able to beare it
when it grew to be a Bull,
in the end he slew it with
his fist, and eate him all in
one day.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="Phago(pn)"><f type="i">Phago<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> did eate in one

more sparingly published,
and therefore lesse pub&shy;

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="asp(n)"><f type="i">Aspe<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a venemous Ser&shy;
pent, that alwaies goe two
and two together, and if
one of them be slaine, the
other will pursue him ea&shy;
gerly that slue him, and if
a man chance to be bitten
by this Serpent, it is pre&shy;
sent death if he cut not
off the member so bitten:
they are of a blacke earth&shy;
ly colour and sometime
yellow. <f type="i">Cleopatra<f type="r"> , by ap&shy;
plying these Serpents to
her body, wilfully slue her
selfe.</xpln>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="basalisk(n)" lexeme="cockatrice(n)"><f type="i">Basaliske<f type="r"> or <f type="i">Cokatrice<f type="r"></form> <xpln>, the
king of all Serpents, as
</page>

<page sig="k3v">
being the most venemous 
of all other, it breaketh
stones, blasteth all plants
with his breath: it bur&shy;
neth euery thing it goeth
ouer, no herbe can grow
neere the place of his a&shy;
bode, it is poyson to poy&shy;
son, and frighteth away all
other Serpents only with
hissing: if a man but touch
it with a long pole it kils
him: if it see a man a&shy;
farre off it destroyes him
with his lookes: it is not
aboue a foot in length, of 
colour betweene blacke
and yellow, hauing very 
red eyes, a very sharpe
head, and a white spot
thereon like a Crowne:
it goeth not winding like
other Serpents, but vp&shy;
right vnto his middle hol&shy;
ding vp his breast: it bree&shy;
deth in the hot burning
sands of <f type="i">Asia<f type="r"> . And seeing 
nature hath framed no&shy;
thing but hath his equall:
this Serpents destruction
is only the Weasell.</xpln>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lexeme="melt(n)"><f type="i">Melt<f type="r"></form>, <xpln> a tree in <f type="i">Mexico<f type="r">,

graue the Iests of Kings,

cures the stinging of Ser&shy;
pents, and the burning

</page>
